paragraphs.title: Paragraph 1
paragraphs.body:
_    Ida Tarbell was one of the first women
"muckrakers" in United States history. 
Muckraking was the Progressive era equivalent
of investigative reporting.  The muckrakers of
this period tracked the movements of trusts,
monopolies, tycoons, and major industries to
bring to light nefarious practices.  Tarbell's
most infamous piece of exposé journalism, The
History of the Standard Oil Company, published
in 1904, attacked John D. Rockefeller's
Standard Oil trust.  This piece was based on
numerous insider interviews and other research. 
She was an extremely courageous woman to
challenge one of the most powerful and credible
businessmen of the day.
